"1626–Deceased","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1520–1579":"1520–1579","1528–1579":"1528–1579","–1628":"–1628","1470–1501":"1470–1501","1475–1528":"1475–1528","1579":"1579","1501":"1501","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1628":"1628","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1626":"1626","Maresfield, Sussex, England":"Maresfield, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roote","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Root  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Root","meanings":["English: perhaps a nickname for a cheerful person, from an unrecorded Middle English <i>rote</i> (Old English <i>rōt</i>) ‘glad, cheerful’.","English: from Middle English <i>rote</i>, <i>route</i>, <i>rotte</i> ‘rote’ (of uncertain origin but apparently ultimately akin to Welsh <i>crwth</i>), perhaps used for a player of the medieval stringed instrument, a kind of harp or fiddle. Compare   Rutter  .","English: perhaps a habitational name from Wroot (Lincolnshire), from Old English <i>wrōt</i> ‘snout, spur of land’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":54,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Roote was born in 1495, in Maresfield, Sussex, England, his father, William Roote, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Doget Boterwyk Butterwick, was 20. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Joan Turke. He died in 1552, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1495–1552":"1495–1552","1626–Female":"1626–Surnud","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1520–1579":"1520–1579","1528–1579":"1528–1579","–1628":"–1628","1470–1501":"1470–1501","1475–1528":"1475–1528","1579":"1579","1501":"1501","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1628":"1628","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1626":"1626","Maresfield, Sussex, England":"Maresfield, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1495–1552":"1495–1552","1626–Female":"1626–Kuollut","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1520–1579":"1520–1579","1528–1579":"1528–1579","–1628":"–1628","1470–1501":"1470–1501","1475–1528":"1475–1528","1579":"1579","1501":"1501","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1475":"1475","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1628":"1628","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","1626":"1626","Maresfield, Sussex, England":"Maresfield, Sussex, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Badby, Northampton